<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-561-722  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 561 722.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  August 21 1989 n552 p79(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Standards, software lend design status to test. (Testing: TheChallenge for the '90s feature)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Runyon, Stan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The trend for the 1990s will see test and measurement activitiestake an equal place alongside design and systems integration.andP;  Themilitary will be a prime force behind this change in the nature ofboth standards and software.andP;  The key requirement of militarysystems is that they be easily serviced and maintained under fieldconditions.andP;  This will lead to self-testing equipment withbuilt-in diagnostic functions.andP;  Contractors and governmentprocurement specialists are already acting upon this realizationand moving toward more flexible standards.andP;  Standardization is thekey by which both military and non-military system testarchitectures can be streamlined and made more efficient andresponsive to the needs of the user.andP;  A similar standardization insoftware design and programming languages will have a major impacton the future of the electronics industry.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computerized TestingStandardsAutomatic Test EquipmentMilitaryElectronicsTesting.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Military standardization via instrument on a card. (chart)Production andamp; DOD test flows: flip-flopped processes. (chart)Testability design and analysis as per MIL-STD-2165. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>